  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical buzzword—it's something I've seen firsthand in my own experiences as a woman working in the electrical trade in Rome. It's that quiet anxiety you feel when you're reminded that your field might not be 'for you' because of who you are. Growing up with parents who had limited formal education, I learned early that success in technical fields often seems to be reserved for those with certain backgrounds. When I started working as an electrician, I'd sometimes catch myself second-guessing my skills in meetings, especially when colleagues made casual comments about 'how smart' they thought I was. This isn't just about confidence—it's about the subtle, everyday pressure that stereotypes create, which can actually impair performance. In my work, I've noticed that when people feel this kind of threat, they might avoid challenging tasks or hesitate to speak up, which can lead to gaps in understanding or even mistakes. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of focusing on changing individual behavior, we need systemic changes—like creating mentorship programs that pair women with experienced electricians who can guide them through the industry's nuances. Also, in my community, we could start conversations in workshops that normalize diverse backgrounds in technical fields. It's not about fixing people; it's about building environments where everyone feels safe to contribute. As someone who's curious about how systems work, I believe that when we address stereotype threat with empathy and practical steps, we don't just help individuals—it helps the whole industry thrive.",
